==English==
===Etymology===
Old English [[fixen]] 'of a fox'. Voiced v- is from Southern dialect

===Noun===
'''vixen''' (''plural'' '''vixens''')

# A [[female]] [[fox]].
# A [[temperamental]] woman.
#:'''1859:''' . . . and if Solomon was as wise as he is reputed to be, I feel sure that when he compared a contentious woman to a contiunal dropping on a very rainy day, he had not a '''vixen''' in his eye&ndash;a fury with long nails, acrid and selfish. - [[w:George Eliot]]. ''Adam Bede'': page 54.  Köln: Könemann Verlagsgesellschaft mbH, 1999
# (''colloquial'') A [[sexy]] woman.

